'''Roger Ibañez da Silva''' ({{IPA|pt|ʁɔˈʒɛʁ iˈbaɲis dɐ ˈsiwvɐ }}; born 23 November 1998) is a Brazilian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]] for [[Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al Ahli Saudi FC|Al-Ahli]] and the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]]. Mainly a centre-back, he can also play as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]].

== Club career ==

=== Early career ===
Born in [[Canela, Rio Grande do Sul]] to a Uruguayan mother, Ibañez only started his career in 2016, aged 18, at {{ill|Grêmio Atlético Osoriense|pt}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/fluminense/noticia/gringo-que-nada-gaucho-ibanez-explica-origem-de-sobrenome-escolhi-por-marketing.ghtml|title=Gringo? Que nada! Gaúcho Ibañez explica origem de nome: "Escolhi por marketing"|trans-title=''Gringo''? Not at all! ''Gaúcho'' Ibañez explains name: "I chose on marketing"|publisher=[[Globo Esporte]]|language=pt-BR|date=8 February 2018|accessdate=11 June 2019|archive-date=26 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026174112/https://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/fluminense/noticia/gringo-que-nada-gaucho-ibanez-explica-origem-de-sobrenome-escolhi-por-marketing.ghtml|url-status=live}}</ref> Playing as a [[midfielder]], he joined {{ill|PRS Futebol Clube|pt}} later in that year, and made his senior debut during the 2016 [[Copa Serrana]], which was the club's first professional competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.portaladesso.com.br/noticias/4954/jogador-revelado-no-prs-garibaldi-vira-titular-do-fluminense.html|title=Jogador revelado no PRS/Garibaldi vira titular do Fluminense|trans-title=Player formed at PRS/Garibaldi becomes a starter at Fluminense|publisher=Portal de Acesso|language=pt-BR|date=23 January 2018|accessdate=11 June 2019|archive-date=26 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026175736/https://www.portaladesso.com.br/noticias/4954/jogador-revelado-no-prs-garibaldi-vira-titular-do-fluminense.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 5 December 2016, Ibañez signed for [[Club Sportivo Sergipe|Sergipe]] on loan for the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/se/futebol/times/sergipe/noticia/2016/12/diretoria-do-sergipe-apresenta-meia-e-volante-para-equipe-de-betinho.html|title=Diretoria do Sergipe apresenta meia e volante para equipe de Betinho|trans-title=Sergipe's board present attacking midfielder and defensive midfielder to Betinho's team|publisher=Globo Esporte|language=pt-BR|date=5 December 2016|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> The following 4 March, however, after featuring rarely, he was recalled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/se/futebol/times/sergipe/noticia/2017/03/mancha-deixa-gerencia-de-futebol-do-sergipe-e-roger-volta-para-o-prs.html|title=Mancha deixa a gerência de futebol do Sergipe e Roger volta para o PRS FC|trans-title=Mancha leaves Sergipe's football management and Roger returns to PRS FC|publisher=Globo Esporte|language=pt-BR|date=4 March 2017|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> Upon returning, he became a regular starter during PRS' [[Campeonato Gaúcho Série B]] campaign.

=== Fluminense ===
In the middle of 2017, Ibañez joined [[Fluminense FC|Fluminense]] and was initially assigned to the under-20 squad. Promoted to the first team for the 2018 season by manager [[Abel Braga]], he made his professional debut on 20 January 2018, starting in a 0–0 [[Campeonato Carioca]] home draw against [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/rj/futebol/campeonato-carioca/jogo/20-01-2018/fluminense-botafogo/|title=Flu pressiona Botafogo no fim, mas equipes não saem do zero em clássico sem graça|trans-title=''Flu'' put pressure on Botafogo in the end, but both teams end up blank in boring derby|publisher=Globo Esporte|language=pt-BR|date=20 January 2018|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref>

On 28 February 2018, Ibãnez had his federative rights purchased by ''Flu'', and he signed a new five-year deal with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://istoe.com.br/fluminense-compra-os-direitos-de-ibanez-e-assina-com-o-zagueiro-por-cinco-anos/|title=Fluminense compra os direitos de Ibañez e assina com o zagueiro por cinco anos|trans-title=Fluminense buy Ibañez's rights and sign with the stopper for five years|publisher=[[Istoé]]|language=pt-BR|date=28 February 2018|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> He made his [[Campeonato Brasileiro Série A|Série A]] debut on 15 April, starting in a 2–1 away loss against [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]], and finished the campaign with 14 league appearances.

=== Atalanta ===
On 29 January 2019, Ibañez signed with Italian club [[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]]|url=https://www.atalanta.it/site/paginalive/prima-squadra/Stagione-2018-2019/2019-01/29-01-Ibanez-firma-per-Atalanta.html|title=Ibañez all'Atalanta|trans-title=Ibañez to Atalanta|date=29 January 2019|language=Italian|access-date=7 February 2019|archive-date=5 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705232842/https://www.atalanta.it/site/paginalive/prima-squadra/Stagione-2018-2019/2019-01/29-01-Ibanez-firma-per-Atalanta.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Having been inserted in the squad in February, he received his debut on 11 May, coming on for the final few minutes of their 2–1 victory over [[Genoa CFC|Genoa]]. He replaced attacker [[Josip Iličić]] as the club was in the heat of battle for a top-four Serie A finish and [[UEFA Champions League]] qualification for the first time in their history, which they eventually achieved.

Ibañez made his first appearance the following season on the final day of Atalanta's [[2019–20 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage campaign in the Champions League]]. Needing a win away to [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]], Ibañez came on for centre-forward [[Luis Muriel]] for the final 20 minutes with Atalanta leading 1–0 and having previously abandoned their regular back three for a back four while in search of the winning goal. Ibañez had only been included in one of the previous five match day squads, but the suspension of [[Rafael Toloi]] and an injury to [[Simon Kjær]] paved the way for his inclusion. Atalanta would win the game 0–3, qualifying for the knockout stage.

=== Roma ===
On 27 January 2020, Ibañez moved to follow Serie A club [[AS Roma|Roma]] and signed a four-and-a-half-year contract with the club. The transfer was initially a loan until 30 June 2021, set to convert to a permanent transfer for a predetermined fee of €8 million if certain conditions were met.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[AS Roma]]|url=https://www.asroma.com/en/news/2020/1/roma-complete-ibanez-addition|title=Roma complete Ibanez addition|date=27 January 2020|access-date=28 January 2020|archive-date=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316040646/https://www.asroma.com/en/news/2020/1/roma-complete-ibanez-addition|url-status=live}}</ref> On 4 March 2021, he signed a new long-term deal with Roma until 30 June 2025.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[AS Roma]]|url=https://www.asroma.com/en/news/2021/3/ibanez-extends-contract-until-2025|title=Ibanez extends contract until 2025|date=4 March 2021}}</ref>

=== Al-Ahli ===
On 10 August 2023, Roger Ibañez joined Saudi club [[Al Ahli Saudi FC|Al-Ahli]] on a permanent transfer,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asroma.com/en/news/69151/roger-ibanez-joins-al-ahli |title=Roger Ibanez joins Al-Ahli |publisher=AS Roma |date=10 August 2023 }}</ref> for a reported fee of €30m including bonuses.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/roger-ibanez-set-to-join-al-ahli-for-nearly-30-million-37989197 |title=Roger Ibanez set to join Al-Ahli for nearly €30 million |publisher=OneFootball |date=7 August 2023 |access-date=10 August 2023 |archive-date=10 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230810232536/https://onefootball.com/de/news/roger-ibanez-set-to-join-al-ahli-for-nearly-30-million-37989197 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 18 August, he scored his first goal for the club in a 3–1 away victory against [[Al-Khaleej FC|Khaleej Club]].

== International career ==
On 9 September 2022, Ibañez received his first call up to the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]], for friendlies against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] and [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Tite convoca a Seleção Brasileira para amistosos contra Gana e Tunísia |url=https://www.cbf.com.br/selecao-brasileira/noticias/selecao-masculina/tite-convoca-a-selecao-brasileira-para-amistosos-contra-gana-e-tunisia |publisher=[[Brazilian Football Confederation|CBF]] |access-date=9 September 2022 |date=9 September 2022 |language=pt |archive-date=4 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221004080903/https://www.cbf.com.br/selecao-brasileira/noticias/selecao-masculina/tite-convoca-a-selecao-brasileira-para-amistosos-contra-gana-e-tunisia |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his debut against Tunisia on 27 September, in a 5–1 win.

In May 2026, Ibañez was included in the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]] 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], marking his first ever World Cup

